In uncertain times, communities come together to look out for one another.

That's why you should consider joining your school's parent teacher association (PTA).

The PTA supports students and teachers.

It's a way for parents to get involved in the education of their children and gives voice to the community.

Get involved. Join your school PTA today.

Questions? Contact Juanita Flores at jflores[at]ssfusd.org.

What happens if you have to stay home from work if you or a family member are under quarantine due to #coronavirus?

California Governor Gavin Newsom says:
shared_text:
EDD.CA.GOV
edd.ca.gov

Gavin Newsom
March 9 at 9:21 PM ·

If a medical professional says you are unable to work due to having or being exposed to the Coronavirus -- you can file a Disability Insurance claim.

If you’re unable to work because you’re caring for a sick or quarantined family member with Coronavirus -- you can file a Paid Family Leave claim.

If you’re unable to work because you’re caring for a sick or quarantined family member with Coronavirus -- you can file a Paid Family Leave claim.

MORE INFO: https://edd.ca.gov/about_edd/coronavirus-2019.htm

New information about #coronavirus courtesy of local medical experts on KRON 4 News:

-Mortality rate of 0.5% in Germany and South Korea is similar to influenza.

-Those most vulnerable to complications from #coronavirus are older than 60 or those who have preexisting/underlying medical conditions.

-Young people in U.S.A. who contract #coronavirus will most likely have no symptoms, and that will be their entire experience.

-Contagion rate of #coronavirus appears to rival that of seasonal flu.

-Proper hygiene including washing hands for 20 seconds is the best way to prevent transmission of germs and bacteria that can cause sickness.

-Treating #coronavirus in normal, healthy individuals is similar to treating the flu: stay hydrated and take fever reducing medicines.

-Free #coronavirus testing for all per Gavin Newsom.

The South San Francisco High School, aka South City High Warriors received the runner up trophy at today’s Central Coast Section (CCS), division 2 championship match, which was played at Del Mar High School in City of San José.

The team spotted Santa Cruz High a goal early in the game and went to work in the second half intent on working their trademark comeback magic.

The Warriors had a quick goal that was nullified by an offsides call and a number of tantalizing breakaways throughout the game, but they could not convert those chances into goals.

Meanwhile, Santa Cruz managed an insurance goal with about 11:00 minutes left in the game, and time ultimately ran out on the Warriors.

Many thanks to coach Brian Mansell and to our @ssfhsconnections varsity girls’ soccer team and to our seniors Alexandra Arouxet-Jara, Leilani Jara, Iliana Sanchez, Camellia Nasrah, Yadia Galindo, and Megan Celillo for helping us reach so far this year! Thank you for a great season! #Believe #GoWarriors

Congresswoman Jackie Speier represents California's 14th congressional district, which includes much of County of San Mateo - Government and a portion of City of San Francisco.

Community engagement in action:

South San Francisco Unified School District's Migrant Education Program enlisted former The City of South San Francisco – Government Mayor Pedro Gonzalez to help commemorate the successful conclusion of a six-week parenting course on December 16.

Gonzalez thanked the parents for participating in the program and also encouraged them to become involved in the civic life of the country by taking part in the 2020 census. #Believe
shared_text:
Jason Innovation
December 19, 2019 at 4:57 PM ·

South San Francisco Unified School District’s Migrant Education Program enlisted former The City of South San Francisco – Government Mayor Pedro Gonzalez to help commemorate the successful conclusion of a six-week parenting course on December 16.

Gonzalez thanked the parents for participating in the program and also encouraged them to become involved in the civic life of the country by taking part in the 2020 census.

The parenting course, entitled Positive Discipline and Mindfulness, was sponsored by South San Francisco Unified School District’s (SSFUSD) Migrant Education Program and Mind Body Moms.

It introduced parents to concepts such as positive discipline and mindfulness practices designed to help them manage stress and reduce emotional reactivity.

Who is Ruby Bridgess and why is she important? Two years ago, Martin Elementary School students petitioned South San Francisco Unified School District and the San Mateo County Office of Education and The City of South San Francisco – Government to commemorate this #CivilRights icon.

Now four school districts in County of San Mateo - Government observe Ruby Bridges Day.

On November 14, students from Parkway Heights Middle School and Martin, Spruce, and Sunshine Gardens Elementary Schools will gather in front of city hall on Grand Avenue at 7:30 AM and walk to their respective schools to pay homage to Ruby Bridges. Join us!

post_text:
For anyone wondering about #airquality, today we are in the 101-150 range. #kincadefire #pgepowershutdown

0 – 50 Good, no health effects

51 – 100 Moderate

101 – 150 Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups

Students and staff with known respiratory conditions, such as asthma, are encouraged to refrain from outdoor activities that involve heavy physical exertion such as athletics.

151 – 200 Unhealthy

School sites will limit prolonged outdoor exposure by moving activities indoors, and if necessary, cancelling events which may not be feasible to conduct indoors. Outdoor exposure must be limited to the best of our collective ability.

201 – 300 Very Unhealthy

Superintendent/Designee may consider closing schools and offices, resulting in students and staff being sent home.

301 – 500 Hazardous

An official emergency will be called.

post_text:
Beginning in 2020, SSFUSD school board members will be chosen through district elections, instead of a citywide vote.

To prepare for this, members of the public were asked over the past several months to help determine the shape of the new voting districts.

National Demographics Corporation, which is working with SSFUSD to handle the transition to district elections, has proposed two maps with different boundaries (map #1 and map #2), while local residents have submitted two maps (map #3 and map #4).

The school board will discuss these four proposals at a fourth and potentially final public hearing during its October 10 board meeting.

https://www.ssfusd.org/2020redistrict

post_text: Dr. Karla Groth joined South San Francisco Unified School District this week as our new Director of Special Projects, Categorical, and English Learner Programs. Dr. Groth comes to us most recently from Encinitas Union School District, where she served as Director of Curriculum, Instruction, and Accountability. Previously, she worked as a principal in the Bonsall Unified School District and Aurora Public Schools, Aurora, CO. Dr. Groth started her career as a bilingual teacher for the Los Angeles Unified School District and has also served as the Senior Director of Assessment and Accountability with the San Diego County Office of Education. Welcome, Dr. Groth!

post_text:
PONDEROSA ELEMENTARY RECEIVES 2019 KENT AWARD!

Ponderosa Elementary's 5th Grade Peer Tutors program was recently selected to receive a Kent Award at the 2019 Kent Awards Ceremony!

The San Mateo County School Boards Association (SMCSBA) announced the 2019 recipients of the J. Russell Kent Awards. San Mateo County School Boards Association represents the governing boards of the County’s 23 local school districts, the Community College District, and the San Mateo County Office of Education.

Named after former San Mateo County Superintendent of Schools J. Russell Kent, the awards were initiated in 1981 to recognize outstanding and innovative programs throughout the county. Applicants must demonstrate that their programs have clear and intentional goals, promote student success, employ a high degree of creativity, and demonstrate transferability.

A big shout out to Principal Erskine, and to all the Ponderosa, staff, students and families!

Ponderosa Elementary School recently recognized as “Top Bay Area Public Schools for Underserved Students” by Innovative Public Schools.

Ponderosa Elementary School is one of 51 schools being recognized this year in Innovate Public Schools’ fourth annual report, “Top Bay Area Public Schools for Underserved Students”, based on the school’s strong results in English and/or math for low-income African American and/or low-income Latino students in the 2017-18 school year. The report will be released publicly in April, followed by an event at which Ponderosa will be honored on Saturday, April 27th.

Congratulations Genentech!

Futurelab recently received the prestigious Excellence in Mentoring Award for Impactful Philanthropy from MENTOR: The National Mentoring Partnership for their innovative approach to supporting young people in SSFUSD through Futurelab.

"For over a decade, Genentech has been an active supporter of the mentoring movement. In 2008 Genentech launched Gene Academy, which provides weekly after-school mentoring to third through fifth graders from the South San Francisco Unified School District (SSFUSD). Each student has two dedicated Genentech volunteer mentors and together they work on homework or participate in hands-on experiments designed to spark enthusiasm for science. Throughout the past 10 years, 2,000 employees have mentored more than 1,000 students..."

post_text:
Power Outage - Buri Buri Elementary School

Based upon new information from PG&E, the power outage at Buri Buri Elementary School is expected to continue through tomorrow afternoon, Friday, January 18th.

School will continue to be in session and will be open for instruction as regularly scheduled. We will also continue to make adjustments as necessary to ensure the safety and well-being of our students and staff.

We encourage students to be dressed warmly in layered clothing, as our heating system is dependent upon power.

Parents/guardians may choose to keep their students at home. Absences for this reason will be excused.

Should we receive any additional information, we will post an update here and will be sure to notify you as soon as we are able.

SSFUSD is proud to share that we were recently awarded a Golden Bell award, provided through the California School Boards Association, for our Sustainable Energy and Education Program. SSFUSD wants to thank our Board of Trustees, administrators, summer school administrators, teachers, classified staff, our students and families, our wonderful community partner ENGIE, and all others who contributed to the success of this fabulous program.

“The CSBA Golden Bell Awards promotes excellence in education and school board governance by recognizing outstanding programs and governance practices of school boards in school districts and county offices of education throughout California. Golden Bell Awards reflect the depth and breadth of education programs and governance decisions supporting these programs that are necessary to address students’ changing needs...South San Francisco USD has developed a pioneering sustainable energy and STEM education program that continues to deliver long-term environmental, financial and community benefits."

SSFUSD Helen Ng Tam Awarded the California League of Schools Region 4’s Middle School Educator of the Year from the California League of Middle Schools!

SSFUSD is extremely proud to share that four SSFUSD teachers were nominated for California League of Schools Region 4’s Educator of the Year! And especially proud of Helen Ng Tam who was selected as region Region 4’s Middle School Educator of the Year!

The four fantastic SSFUSD teachers honored are as follows:

Helen Ng Tam, Parkway Heights Middle School
Corinna Low, Westborough Middle School
SeaAnna Patrick, El Camino High School (South San Francisco)
Rhonda Clements, South San Francisco High School, aka South City High

The CLS Educator of the Year award is given annually to California elementary, middle, and high school educators who exemplify educational excellence and have made significant efforts to implement elements of educational reform.

post_text:
Air Quality Update - OPEN - 11/18/2019 - 2:15 PM
Dear SSFUSD Community:

According to the Bay Area Air Quality Management District (BAAQMD) and U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) AIRNow index, air quality levels have substantially improved over the weekend.

As these improved conditions are expected to continue into next week, we have determined that our schools will be OPEN as regularly scheduled on Monday, November 19th, and Tuesday, November 20th.

(Please note that our district observes school holidays on Wednesday, November 21st through Friday, November 23rd)

While we are following the Air Quality Forecast, we will also be actively monitoring conditions in South San Francisco and all local areas of our schools. If conditions change, we will post an update and communicate with our schools to ensure our community remains informed.

SSFUSD Air Quality Update

As fire crews continue to battle the Butte County Fire in northern CA, air quality will likely stay in the Unhealthy range for the remainder of the week. Please be aware that our schools will remain OPEN and we will be continuing to enact our limited outdoor activity protocol until further notice. If conditions change, we will post an update and communicate with our schools to ensure our community remains informed.

For the most recent information and changes in air quality status please visit:

Bay Area Air Quality Management District (BAAMQD): http://www.baaqmd.gov/

AIRNow: https://cfpub.epa.gov/airnow/index.cfm?action=airnow.local_city&cityid=317

post_text: Dr. Shawnterra Moore live on KTVU Fox 2 earlier this week talking about Genentech's recently donated Science Garage located on South San Francisco High School, aka South City High's campus.
text: Dr. Shawnterra Moore live on KTVU Fox 2 earlier this week talking about Genentech's recently donated Science Garage located on South San Francisco High School, aka South City High's campus.

post_text:
We had an amazing ribbon-cutting ceremony this past Tuesday on the campus of the South San Francisco High School, aka South City High, we were joined by more than 250 students, community partners, media and elected officials, including the Mayor of The City of South San Francisco – Government. It was great to see so many of you there, and we truly appreciate your support throughout the broader Futurelab journey.

Starting this school year, the Genentech donated custom-built Science Garage will house our newly launched biotech pathway giving local SSFUSD high school students the chance to explore biotechnology, helping to ignite a passion for STEM careers.

THANK YOU Genentech for you ongoing support!

Become a STEM Superstar by joining the STEM Learning Ecosystems for fantastic STEM learning opportunities throughout the summer. The STEM Summer Series will provide free drop-in STEM learning opportunities for kids 3-13 years old - all children must be accompanied by an adult. The Summer STEM Series will take place every Saturday through the summer at the Community Learning Center, 520 Tamarack Lane, South San Francisco. Space is limited, so plan to arrive early.

What’s simply fantastic…

Team WKBK 5.3 is bringing the highly coveted Helix Cup to Westborough Middle School (South San Francisco). Yesterday, 3 teams from each middle school were challenged with creating centrifuges using salad spinners and other common household items in the Helix Cup finale held on the Genentech campus. Team members Julian Tumaliuan, Jonathan Lam, Dylan Hadden and Marco Salonga walked away with first place prize and the Helix Cup! Simply fantastic job WKBK 5.3 and all the teams that competed in the finals!

post_text:
What’s simply fantastic…

On Saturday, April 22nd the Spruce Elementary school community came together and celebrated 100 years of educational excellence. Congresswoman Jackie Speier, Spruce alumna, kicked off the event presenting current principal, Mr. Israel Castillo, with a Congressional Record, which permanently marks the occasion on the official record of the proceedings of the United States Congress. SSFUSD School Board President Ms. Rosa Acosta and SSFUSD Superintendent Dr. Shawnterra Moore presented Mr. Castillo with a beautiful plaque, which will be permanently placed in front of the school along with a donated Spruce tree. Big thanks to former Assembly member and former South San Francisco Council member Mr. Gene Mullin, who emceed the event, Council members Ms. Karly Matsumoto and Mr. Mark Addiego, and former SSFUSD principal and SSFUSD Board member, Mr. Emanuel (Midge) Damonte, for speaking at the event. Lastly, big thanks to all the committee members who planned a simply fantastic event!

What's simply fantastic...
The students pictured are members of the top three 8th grade teams from each middle school who will be competing for the highly coveted Helix Cup on Tuesday, May 2nd at Genentech. The teams participated in three design challenges at their respective sites – Alta Loma Middle School (South San Francisco), Parkway Heights Middle, and Westborough Middle School (South San Francisco) - and accumulated the top three team scores.

Simply fantastic job teams! Good luck!

What's simply fantastic... the San Mateo County Board of Supervisors recently awarded Mr. Joe Toy and Ms. Corinna Low, both from Westborough Middle School (South San Francisco), the prestigious Math and Science Teacher Innovation Award for their amazing work with our youth!

Moreover, Mr. Daniel Rivera, El Camino High School (South San Francisco), and Ms. Linda Hambrick, South San Francisco High School, aka South City High were also recognized for their participation in the Ignited Stanford Summer Research Program.

Simply fantastic job everyone! Thank you for your unwavering dedication!

SSFHS Sports Broadcasting Program

Jason Innovation
March 24, 2017 at 9:09 AM · YouTube ·

What's simply fantastic...Mr. Aaron Boyd’s South San Francisco High School, aka South City High Video Art Sports Broadcasting Program was recently highlighted at the San Mateo County Career Technical Education Steering Committee Meeting, which was held on Wednesday, March 22nd San Mateo County Office of Education. The Sports Broadcast Program produces over 40 live sports events a year which are broadcast on the NFHS Network and are available to watch afterward on our YouTube page: youtube/southcityvideoart. Students are trained in all the aspects of live video production in a real world setting which produces a professional event that benefits not only students, but promotes school athletics and positively represents our school in the community.The class produced a fantastic video showcasing their behind the scenes sport broadcasting work.

Simpy fantastic job Mr. Boyd and all SSFHS Video Art students!
